Stands are support for the rider's feet that hang down on each side of the saddle.
They provide greater stability for the rider but may cause safety problems due to the risk of a rider’s feet sticking to them.
If a rider falls off the horse but has a foot caught in the ladder, he or she may be drawn if the horse runs away.
First, many riders wear riding boots with a heel and a soft, narrow sole.
Next, some saddles, especially English saddles, have safety belts that make the straps detach from the saddle if they are pulled backward by a falling rider.[citation needed]
