Japanese work culture is more hierarchical and formal than what Westerners are used to.
Jackets are standard business clothing, and colleagues appeal to each other by their surname or job titles.
Harmony at work is important and therefore emphasises group work rather than praise for individual performance.
Workers often need to have their superiors’ decisions and are expected to obey their superiors’ instructions without asking questions.
